Main plot

Below is the most important plot. We want to be like S. Korea or lower. This is a comparison of growth per capita, where day 1 is approx 0.0004% of the countrys population. In reality, we want to know what percentage of hospital beds have been taken up, and so population is just a proxy. The dashed grey lines show epidemic growth when the fraction of infected population doubles every 2 days, or 3 days, etc.

World data

This plot shows the spread of the virus over time across the world. We want the number of active cases to drop to 0, the deaths to stay as low as possible obviously, and the recovered cases (blue) to climb high. Confirmed is a cumulative count of everyone that has tested positive.

These plots show how the numbers have grown over time in each country. All countries want to hit the bent curve that China has reported achieving.

Massachusetts Data

MA data from https://github.com/b-lev/massachusetts-covid19-report-archive.

The cumulative fraction of MA covid patients that are hospitalized.

MA is performing an increasing (but still inadequate) number of tests per day.

US Testing Statistics

Testing in each state. Based on https://covidtracking.com/api/states/daily.csv. Sometimes, health care workers are tested, to be sure they are not infected. That is one explanation for why some states show many negatives.

This plots show how long it is taking each state to test its population, on a per capita basis. (Im assuming, optimistically, that the test had not be given to the same person twice.)

Thanks to JHU for the data (https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19). Results are only as good as the data, which is only as good as the amount of testing done.
